  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH) Assistance to Vulnerable Migrant Populations in Urban and Hard to Reach (HTR) Areas in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">According to the Afghanistan Humanitarian Response Plan (HRP) there were over 8.8 million people in need of water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) support in 2021. The risk of severe drought was also recognized by the Afghanistan National Disaster Management Authority (ANDMA), which released a&#x202F;National Drought Response Contingency Plan&#x202F;in April 2021 and an official state of drought was declared in June. Based on the needs assessments, it is clear that access to safe and clean water is a challenge in many provinces, where households rely on unprotected water sources, unstable piped water and, for a minority, surface water. Further, the lack of water points, and distance to collect water, also heightens the risk of gender-based-violence. This project directly contributes to identified WASH needs by expanding water provision through rehabilitation of gravity water supply schemes, hand-dug wells and boreholes, repair and set-up of handpumps and water distribution systems, and enhancing household water treatment and storage capacity. IOM is also providing hand hygiene infrastructure, hygiene kits, inclusive of menstrual hygiene management items, and conduct hygiene promotion activities to improve public health and reduce the risk of WASH-related diseases in high needs and/or hard to reach locations.</narrative>
  </description>
